\begin{abstract}
  Water resources in the Indian portion of the Indo-Gangetic Plain are increasingly threatened by population growth, agricultural intensification, urbanisation and climate change. Considering the region's scale, as well as its biophysical, socioeconomic and institutional complexity, we argue that a systems approach is required to achieve food and water security under future development and climate change scenarions. We present a conceptual system dynamics model which aims to elucidate the key feedbacks and interactions between diverse, interconnected systems. We highlight key challenges associated with the implementation of the model, which include issues such as model resolution, integrating climate forecasts and data scarcity. To conclude, we assert that system dynamics modelling is an approapriate tool for analysing water resources in the Indo-Gangetic Plain and suggest that, ultimately, the model could be used for developing policy options and strategies for promoting sustainable water resources management in the basin. 
\end{abstract}

