\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Managing the water resources of the Indo-Gangetic Plain is a complex task because of the basin's unique scale as well as the complexity of its biophysical, institutional and socioeconomic characteristics. Land use in this highly fertile and densely populated region is dominated by intensive agriculture \citep{shah_is_2009}. This has been the case for at least 2000 years \citep{}; however, a step-change in agricultural productivity since India's green revolution, initiated in the mid-1960s, combined with unmanaged and inefficient water abstraction for irrigation, has resulted in the degradation of both the quantity and quality of water resources \citep{}. Currently, irrigation accounts for more than 85\% of total water use, with up to 55\% of the net irrigated are supplied from groundwater \citep{narula_challenges_2009}. The agricultural sector continues to be an important part of India's economy, employing more than 60\% of the working population and contributing around 18\% to the country's gross domestic product \citep{varua_assisting_2016}. Water use is directly linked to the energy sector, with groundwater pumping for irrigation accounting for around 30\% of the total electricity consumption \citep{narula_challenges_2009} and between 4-6\% of the total carbon emissions \citep{shah_indias_2009}. Rapid urbanisation has reduced infiltration and recharge to groundwater, while simultaneously reducing the area of cropland. The use of former irrigation wells by private consumers in newly-urbanised areas adds further complexity to the urban water system \citep{srinivasan_impact2013}. Meanwhile the Ganga and its tributaries provide important habitats for culturally important, yet critically endangered, species such as the Gharial crocodile and Ganges river dophin \citep{choudhary_river_2012}, as well as supporting the livelihoods of inland fishing communities, which are among India's most marginalised \citep{}. \\

Water management in the Indo-Gangetic Plain is complicated by local regulations and governance structures which impede cross-sectoral cooperation and promote competition for scarce water resources \citep{tiwari_issues_2015}. The basin's groundwater resources, a primary source of irrigation and rural water supply to millions, are developed and managed independently by multiple agencies \citep{}. The socioeconomic heterogeneity of the Indo-Gangetic Plain has important implications both for farmer livelihood and food and water security. In the western states of Punjab, Haryana and western Uttar Pradesh, substantial government subsidies for electricity combined with perverse incentives to grow certain crops has led to unsustainable cropping practices and falling groundwater levels \citep{rodell_satellite_2009,macdonald_groundwater_2016}. Nevertheless, farmers in this region tend to be more prosperous than their counterparts in eastern Uttar Pradesh and Bihar, who typically rely on inefficient and comparatively expensive diesel pumps for groundwater abstraction \citep{shah_irrigation_2009}. As a result, the eastern part of the Indo-Gangetic Plain has been characterised as one of ``low productivity but high potential'' \citep{shah_irrigation_2009}, and creating the conditions in which the groundwater can be accessed sustainably is seen as the key to alleviating rural poverty while meeting India's growing food demand. \\

Managing ecosystems - global analysis \citep{jaegermeyr_reconciling_2017}. While global analyses are useful... they typically cannot represent complexities at the local to regional level [the level at which policy decisions are made] which influence the relationship between food production and ecosystems. In this paper, we describe the development of a socio-hydrological model to assess the sustainability of food production in the Gandak river basin, a tributary of the Ganges located in northern India. \\

The competition for water resources between human activities and the environment has been widely studied, particularly in the context of... \citet{van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014} developed a system dynamics model to represent the socio-hydrology of the Murrumbidgee River basin in Australia. Here, the authors note a ``pendulum swing'' from human activities driven by agricultural intensification at the expense of the environment, towards behaviour which considered environmental preservation... \\

The pressure on water resources in the Indo-Gangetic Plain will intensify in the future. India's population is not expected to stabilise until around 2060, when it will have grown to 1.72 billion from 1.21 billion in 2011, with the highest growth rate occurring in urban areas \citep{james_indias_2016}. Climate change is expected to increase the interannual and intraseasonal variability of the South Asian monsoon \citep{turner_climate_2012,singh_observed_2014}, which supplies up to 80\% of the region's water resources. In this context, achieving food and water security requires interdisciplinary collaboration across sectors, communities and institutions. A necessary first step towards this goal is to develop a comprehensive understanding of the complex dynamics of the Indo-Gangetic Plain system. System dynamics modelling, which provides a formal representation of the interactions and feedbacks between disparate but connected subsystems in order to elicit the behaviour of the system as a whole \citep{mirchi_synthesis_2012}, has been shown to be an effective tool for enabling sustainable water resources management \citep{mirchi_synthesis_2012}. This paper presents a roadmap towards a system dynamics model of the Indian portion of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, which is being developed as part of a multidisciplinary consortium consisting of researchers and practitioners from UK and Indian institutions. The aim of the model is to advance understanding and quantification of the human natural system and provide a foundation for an improved water management framework for the Indo-Gangetic Plain. \\

In this paper we present a system dynamics model to gain insight into the competition for water resources between agricultural activities and the environment in the Gandak River basin, a subbasin of the Ganges in which river discharge is influenced by a large barrage on the India-Nepal border. System dynamics... The model... a formal representation of the structure of the system in order to better understand its response to exogenous and endogenous change. Ultimately, we aim to provide a model which is capable of assessing the efficacy of potential policy interventions to improve the environmental health of the river basin whilst maintaining or improving rural livelihoods and food production in the region. \\

