\section{Methods}
\label{sec:meth}

The development of system dynamics models follows a clear framework which informs system understanding \citep{blair_socio-hydrological_2016}. System conceptualisation, usually in the form of a causal loop diagram, determines key system components and the linkages and feedbacks that exist between them. The conceptual model is transformed to a stocks and flows diagram, which involves the qualitative identification of key system resources (``stocks'') and the various processes which cause these to change over time (``flows''). Data and model equations are included in the stocks and flows diagram, resulting in a quantitative system dynamics model. Here, we describe the conceptualisation of the water resources of the Indo-Gangetic Plain system and propose methodologies for moving towards a quantitative framework. Broadly, the model can be considered in terms of the water supply and water demand subsystems, which are described in more detail below.

