\subsection{Water demand}

\subsubsection{Irrigation}
The root zone is conceptualized as a bucket with storage equal to the \textit{total available water} ($\mathrm{M L^{-2}}$),

\begin{equation}
  TAW = (\theta_{fc} - \theta_{wp}) Z_{r}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\theta_{fc}$ and $\theta_{wp}$ are the water contents at field capacity and wilting point, respectively, and $R_{z}$ is maximum rooting depth. The \textit{readily available water}, RAW, is the proportion of TAW that can be extracted from the root zone before the soil moisture deficit impedes crop growth,

\begin{equation}
  RAW = (1-p)TAW
\end{equation}

\noindent where $p$ is the crop-specific depletion factor.\\

The daily water balance equation expressed in terms of root zone depletion, $D_{r}$ ($\mathrm{L}$), is written

\begin{equation}
\frac{dD_{r}}{dt}(t,T)\Delta t = ET_{c}(t,T) + R(t,T) - \big(P(t,T) - RO(t,T)\big) - I(t,T)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $ET_{c}$ ($\mathrm{L}$) is actual crop evapotranspiration, $R$ ($\mathrm{L}$) is recharge, $P$ ($\mathrm{L}$) is precipitation, $RO$ ($\mathrm{L}$) is surface runoff and $I$ ($\mathrm{L}$) is irrigation. Crop evapotranspiration is determined as

\begin{equation}
ET_{c}(t,T) = K_{s}(t,T)K_{c}(t,T)ET_{0}(t,T)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $K_{c}$ is a crop coefficient which varies according to the crop growth, $K_{s}$ is a water stress coefficient and $ET_{0}$ ($\mathrm{L}$) is reference evapotranspiration. Crop coefficients are obtained from the FAO \citep{Allen1998}. The water stress coefficient is calculated:

\begin{equation}
K_{s}(t,T) = \frac{TAW-D_{r}(t,T)}{\big(1-p\big)TAW}.
\end{equation}

\noindent We assume that surface runoff and groundwater recharge occur when the root zone water content exceeds field capacity. Following \citet{mackay_lumped_2014}, the division of excess water between these two components is controlled using the baseflow index, $BFI$, ... Soil drainage is thus computed

\begin{equation}
  R =
  \begin{cases}
    -D_{r} BFI & \text{if} D_{r} < 0\\
    0          & \text{otherwise}
  \end{cases}
\end{equation}

\noindent and surface runoff is the difference between the total excess water and recharge.\\

The groundwater component of the model is based on AquiMod \citep{mackay_lumped_2014}, a spatially lumped conceptual groundwater model. In this model the attenuation of soil drainage by the unsaturated zone is modelled using the Weibull probability density function, written as

\begin{equation}
  f(x;\lambda,k) =
  \begin{cases}
    \frac{k}{\lambda}\left(\frac{x}{\lambda}\right)e^{(-x/\lambda)^{k})} & x \geq 0,\\
    0                                                                  & x < 0
  \end{cases}
  \label{eq:weibull}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\lambda$ is the scale parameter and $k$ is the shape parameter, which respectively control the location of the peak and the spread of the function around the peak. Recharge is then distributed over a set number of time steps, $n$, such that recharge at time $t$ is calculated:

\begin{equation}
  R(t) = \alpha \sum_{x=1}^{n} f(x) SD_{t-x+1}
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\alpha$ is a scaling parameter which ensures the discrete integral of Eq.~\ref{eq:weibull} equals one.

We estimate the change in groundwater head at each time step with the following mass balance calculation:

\begin{equation}
  R(t) \delta x \delta y - Q(t) = S \delta x \delta y \frac{dh}{dt}(t)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\delta x$ and $\delta y$ are the length and width of the aquifer, $Q$ is groundwater discharge ($\mathrm{L^3}$), $S$ is the dimensionless storage coefficient and $h$ is the groundwater head (L). \\

\subsubsection{Domestic}
We compute domestic water demand using gridded population estimates multipled by the per capita water consumption for the region. We assume that all domestic water is abstracted from the groundwater resource, based on information collected in the field. 

