\subsubsection{Environment}
We model ecological demand in terms of the suitability of the river and riparian zone to the Gharial crocodile and Ganges river dophin. This was assessed using a river network model developed using MIKE... and a coupled surface water groundwater model. Within the system dynamics model, a simplified model is used which computes relative habitat suitability based on the barrage release and the groundwater level.

\subsection{Water supply}

\subsubsection{Surface water}
The barrage at Valmikinagar supplies two irrigation canals, east and west branches. We obtained the design inflows to the respective canals for each month of the year from the original agreement between Nepal and India. Water distribution across the canal command area is highly uneven, with farmers nearer the canal head typically receiving more water than their counterparts nearer the tail. To model the distribution of canal water we start from the assumption that in a perfect system irrigated land should receive an equal volume of canal water regardless of its position within the command area. Such a situation is unlikely to occur due to imperfect management practices, seepage and evaporation losses, lack of maintenance of canal infrastructure and overabstraction of water by farmers closer to the canal head \citep{}. The canal system was designed assuming seepage losses of 30\%, but subsequent estimates have put this figure at closer to XYZ\%. To model seepage losses we consider the canal network in terms of the main canal network, which distributes water acoss the entire command area, and its secondary and tertiary components which take water from the main channels to the fields where the water is used (Figure~\ref{}). \\

\subsubsection{Groundwater}
Hydrology in the Indo-Gangetic Plain is groundwater dominated \citep{shah_is_2009}. In the past, the underlying alluvial aquifer has been considered as a homogeneous system with uniform physical properties. However, recent observational analysis has shown that the hydrogeology is complex and highly heterogeneous \citep{macdonald_groundwater_2016}. Groundwater levels in the basin, which to a large extent influence accessibility to the resource \citep{}, respond to groundwater extraction rates and recharge from rainfall, irrigation and surface water; all of which vary in time and space.  Groundwater also influences river baseflow, which is an important constraint on the habitats of important species \citep{choudhary_river_2012}. \\

Groundwater recharge is computed as the sum of deep percolation from the root zone and canal seepage. We represent the aquifer using a simple 1-dimensional groundwater model based on the approach outlined in \citet{okeeffe_including_2018}. We assume the aquifer is unconfined, with uniform depth to bedrock and specific yield, $S_{y}$, which defines the ``volume of water released from storage by an unconfined aquifer per unit surface area per unit decline of the water table''. 

We assume that groundwater is used for irrigation if the canal supply does not meet the crop water demand. The amount of groundwater extracted is a function of the number of tubewells in the polygon, the tubewell capacity ($\mathrm{L^{3}T^{-1}}$) and the number of hours the pump can be operated during the day ($\mathrm{T}$), which itself is related to the price of diesel and the financial resources of the farmer. 

