Within each grid cell we consider a representative ``farmer''.

\subsection{Income}
We assume that farm income arises from the sale of crops and/or labour. The crop yield model is based on that presented in \citet{pande_sociohydrological_2016}, in which the maximum crop yield, $Y_{max}$ ($\mathrm{ML^{-2}}$) is linearly scaled according to limiting factors, $\beta_{N}$, $\beta_{\ell_{y_{c}}}$ and $\beta_{e_{c}}$, which respectively account for restrictions in the availability of nutrients, labour and water. \\

To account for nutrient availability we first define the minimum yield,

\begin{equation}
  Y_{min} = \frac{F(T)}{n_{min}}
\end{equation}

% TODO: introduce crop index
\noindent where $F(T)$ is soil fertility and $n_{min}$ is the minimum nitrogen requirement of the crop \citep{pande_sociohydrological_2016}. Yield is increased from its minimum value through the application of fertiliser, $n_{m}$ ($M$), up to an optimal value, $F_{max}$ ($M$). Hence we define $\beta_{N}$ as follows:

\begin{equation}
  \beta_{N}(T) =
  \begin{cases}
    b                                                 & \text{if} \frac{{n_m(T)}{A_{c}F_{max}} = 0\\
    b + (1 - b)\left(\frac{n_{m}}{A_{c}F_{max}}\right) & \text{if} 0 < \frac{n_m}{A_{c}F_{max}} \leq 1\\
    1                                                 & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\label{eq:nutrient-limiter}
\end{equation}  

\noindent where

\begin{equation}
  b = \frac{Y_{min}}{Y_{max}}.
\end{equation}

Yield reduction due to labour availability is the ratio of the labour devoted to crop production, $\ell_{y_{c}}(T)$ and its optimal value, $\ell_{y_{c}}^{max}$, as follows:

\begin{equation}
  \Beta_{\ell_{y_{c}}}(T) =
  \begin{cases}
    \frac{\ell_{y_{c}}(T)}{\ell_{y_{c}}^{max}} & \text{if} \ell_{y_{c}}(T) < \ell_{y_{c}}^{max}
    1                                        & \text{otherwise}
  \end{cases}
  \label{eq:labour-limiter}
\end{equation}

Lastly, the reduction in yield as a consequence of lack of water is modelled using the approach developed by \citet{Doorenbos1979a}, which is expressed

\begin{equation}
\left(1-\frac{Y_{a}(T)}{Y_{x}(T)}\right) = K_{y}\left(1-\frac{\sum\limits_{t=d_{s}}^{d_{h}} ET_{c}(t)}{\sum\limits_{t=d_{s}}^{d_{h}} ET_{x}(t)}\right)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $Y_{x}$ is maximum yield, $Y_{a}$ is actual yield, $K_{y}$ is the yield response factor, $ET_{x}$ is maximum evapotranspiration, $ET_{c}$ is actual crop evapotranspiration, $d_{s}$ is sowing day and $d_{h}$ is harvesting day. \\

Crop price is an exogenous variable...\\

In common with several other socio-hydrological models \citep[e.g.][]{van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014}, we introduce a technological change variable, $T$, in order to account for several variables which we do not model explicitly. Following \citep{van_emmerik_socio-hydrologic_2014}, we define technological change as a function of the \textit{gross basin product} (GBP; the total income within the basin over a given year), as follows:

\begin{equation}
  T = \left(\lambda_{1} + \lambda_{2} e^{-\eta P_{GB}}\right)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\lambda_{1}$, $\lambda_{2}$ and $\eta$ are parameters.\\

\subsection{Expenditure}

\subsubsection{Operating expenses}
% Detail ongoing expenses such as fuel costs, 
We estimate the volume of diesel, $\nu_{d}$, required to abstract a unit volume of water from depth $h$ with a ... pump using an empirical relationship derived at the University of Nebraska \citep{martin_2003}, written as

\begin{equation}
  \nu_{d} = \frac{0.1133 h(t,T) + 0.7949}{102.87} \eta
\end{equation}

\noindent where $\eta$ is pump efficiency. Expenditure on fuel is thus computed

\begin{equation}
  m_{a}(T) = \sum\limits_{t=1}^{365} \nu_{d} \times I(t,T) \times q_{d}(T)
\end{equation}

\noindent where $q_{d}$ is the unit price of diesel.\\

The required quantity of fertiliser is the difference between the nitrogen requirement and that provided by livestock \citep{}. \\

At the end of the year any surplus capital is transferred to a savings account. This is used as a buffer within the agricultural year, as well as to make investments to improve the perception of water security. \\

