\section{Sociohydrology of the Gandak basin}

\subsection{Competition for resources in the Gandak basin}
Water resources in the Gandak basin are mediated by the barrage at Valmikinagar on the India-Nepal border. The barrage and its canal system was constructed in ? to supply water to two irrigation command areas: the western branch canal supplies farmers in Nepal and Uttar Pradesh, and the eastern branch canal which supplies farmers in Bihar. \\

Despite the canal supply, the number of tubewells in the districts within the command area has increased dramatically in recent decades, in line with much of the rest of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, while the irrigated area supplied by canals has gradually fallen (Figure X). Interviewed farmers suggested that a lack of maintenance of the canal network is likely to be an important driver of this pattern. While in the Gandak basin groundwater levels are stable, much of the rural area is not covered by a reliable electricity supply and hence farmers must rely on costly diesel pumps to abstract water for irrigation. Previous research in the Indo-Gangetic Plain \citep{} has shown that smallholder farmers in the region are yield maximisers, as opposed to profit maximisers. \\

Downstream of the barrage, the Gandak river provides a habitat for culturally important riverine species including the Gharial crocodile and Ganges river dolphin. \\

