\subsection{Climate forcing data}
We used a daily gridded precipitation product from the Indian Meteorological Department \citep{}. Reference evapotranspiration was retrieved from the ECMWF reanalysis product \citep{}. Socioeconomic data was obtained from subnational inventory data. \\

\subsection{Parameterisation}

\subsubsection{Soil properties}
Soil properties were obtained from the HiHydroSoil database \citep{}. Crop parameters, including crop coefficient and depletion factor, were obtained from local experimental data where available \citep[e.g.][]{}, otherwise FAO irrigation and drainage paper 56 \citep{allen}. 

\subsubsection{Potential crop yield}
% http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/gaez/docs/GAEZ_Model_Documentation.pdf
% page 113, para 2
Values of potential crop yield, which are multipled by the various limiting factors to estimate the actual crop yield, are obtained from the FAO Global Agro-Ecological Zones database \citep{}. The maps available from FAO GAEZ show the agro-climatic potential crop yield for irrigated and rainfed crops at high, intermediate and low input levels. Following the FAO GAEZ methodology to estimate yield gaps \citep{}, we use crop suitability maps, also produced by FAO GAEZ, to estimate the likely input level in a given pixel. We assume the the best quality land has high agricultural inputs and management practices, moderately suitable land has intermediate inputs and marginal land has low input level. 

\subsubsection{Initial values of sociological variables}
Various socioeconomic values were obtained from India's Minor Irrigation Census, which was first carried out in 1986/87. The area irrigated by surface water and groundwater, and the area of each crop, was obtained from annual agricultural inventory data. \\

